<div1 type="segment" n="A">
<lg id="t.6.1.14.1" type="proverb" n="14.1"><p id="t6114.p1" n="1" corresp="c6114.A.14.1.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. B l. 1</xref></note>
Let the favour be repaid to him who repays a favour.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.2" type="proverb" n="14.2"><p id="t6114.p2" n="2" corresp="c6114.A.14.2.2">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.2.5" from="t625.h32">6.2.5: NBC 8072</xref></note>
May <w type="DN">Luma</w> grant prosperity to him 
<addSpan to="t6114.v1"/>who speaks well of others
<anchor id="t6114.v1"/>
<addSpan to="t6114.v2"/><note lang="eng">1 ms. has instead:</note> who has good things
<anchor id="t6114.v2"/>.</p>
</lg>
<altGrp><alt targType="addSpan" targets="t6114.v1 t6114.v2"/></altGrp><lg id="t.6.1.14.3" type="proverb" n="14.3"><p id="t6114.p3" n="3-4" corresp="c6114.A.14.3.3">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.16" from="t.6.1.16.c1">6.1.16.c1</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. A ll. 7-8</xref></note>
The farmer lifts his gaze to you <note lang="eng">i.e. <w type="DN">Enlil</w></note>: <q>May <w type="DN">Enlil</w> look upon the city that he cursed.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.4" type="proverb" n="14.4"><p id="t6114.p4" n="5-6" corresp="c6114.A.14.4.5">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.15" from="t.6.1.15.b1">6.1.15.b1</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.16" from="t.6.1.16.c2">6.1.16.c2</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. A ll. 9-10</xref></note>
The herdsman lifts his gaze to you: <q>May <w type="DN">Enlil</w> look upon the city that he cursed.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.5" type="proverb" n="14.5"><p id="t6114.p5" n="7-8" corresp="c6114.A.14.5.7">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.15" from="t.6.1.15.b2">6.1.15.b2</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.16" from="t.6.1.16.c3">6.1.16.c3</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. A ll. 11-12</xref></note>
The potter lifts his gaze to you: <q>May <w type="DN">Enlil</w> look upon the city that he cursed.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.6" type="proverb" n="14.6"><p id="t6114.p6" n="9-11" corresp="c6114.A.14.6.9">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.149">6.1.03.149</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.16" from="t.6.1.16.c5">6.1.16.c5</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.22">6.1.22: ll. 172-175</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.1">6.1.25.1</xref></note>
The day became cloudy but it did not rain. It rained, but not enough for people to undo their sandals. The <w type="WN">Tigris</w> was not surging at its inlet, so water did not fill the arable lands.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.7" type="proverb" n="14.7"><p id="t6114.p7" n="12-14" corresp="c6114.A.14.7.12">
<gap extent="3 lines fragmentary"/>
<gap extent="approx. 5-10 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="B">
<lg id="t.6.1.14.15" type="proverb" n="14.15"><p id="t6114.p8" n="1" corresp="c6114.B.14.15.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.68">6.1.01.68</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.6">6.1.25.6</xref></note>
You should drive them like pack-asses into a death-stricken city.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.16" type="proverb" n="14.16"><p id="t6114.p9" n="2-3" corresp="c6114.B.14.16.2">
The temple <w type="TN">E-babbar</w>, which <w type="RN">Me-silim</w> had built, was destroyed by <w type="DN">Nanni</w>, whose posterity had been cut off.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.17" type="proverb" n="14.17"><p id="t6114.p10" n="4" corresp="c6114.B.14.17.4">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.143">6.1.02.143</xref></note>
If a household has harmed an acquaintance, the matter should be investigated.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.18" type="proverb" n="14.18"><p id="t6114.p11" n="5-6" corresp="c6114.B.14.18.5">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.92">6.1.03.92</xref>, <xref doc="t.4.05.1">4.05.1: ll. 54-55</xref></note>
<w type="DN">Enlil's</w> temple is a collecting (?) of wages (?); yet to reach out, to look with greedy eyes and to seize should be abominations there.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.19" type="proverb" n="14.19"><p id="t6114.p12" n="7" corresp="c6114.B.14.19.7">
Both the palace and the nether world require obedience from their inhabitants.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.20" type="proverb" n="14.20"><p id="t6114.p13" n="8-10" corresp="c6114.B.14.20.8">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.157">6.1.02.157</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.11">6.1.25.11</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.3" from="t623.h27">6.2.3: UET 6/2 317</xref></note>
A palace cannot ignore waste land. A barge cannot ignore straw. A freeborn man cannot ignore toil.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.21" type="proverb" n="14.21"><p id="t6114.p14" n="11-12" corresp="c6114.B.14.21.11">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.153">6.1.02.153</xref></note>
The palace is an ox; you should catch it by the tail. <w type="DN">Utu</w> is lord; you should fix your gaze on him.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.22" type="proverb" n="14.22"><p id="t6114.p15" n="13-14" corresp="c6114.B.14.22.13">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.158">6.1.02.158</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.17" from="t.6.1.17.b9">6.1.17.b9</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.10">6.1.25.10</xref></note>
The palace: one day a mother giving birth, the next day a mother in mourning.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.23" type="proverb" n="14.23"><p id="t6114.p16" n="15" corresp="c6114.B.14.23.15">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.156">6.1.02.156</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.8">6.1.25.8</xref></note>
The palace is a slippery place &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.24" type="proverb" n="14.24"><p id="t6114.p17" n="16" corresp="c6114.B.14.24.16">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.37" type="proverb" n="14.37"><p id="t6114.p18" n="17" corresp="c6114.B.14.37.17">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.38" type="proverb" n="14.38"><p id="t6114.p19" n="18" corresp="c6114.B.14.38.18">
&X;&X; a river &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.39" type="proverb" n="14.39"><p id="t6114.p20" n="19-20" corresp="c6114.B.14.39.19">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.160">6.1.01.160</xref></note>
Having wives is human. Having children is from the gods.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.40" type="proverb" n="14.40"><p id="t6114.p21" n="21-22" corresp="c6114.B.14.40.21">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.151">6.1.01.151</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.28" from="t.6.1.28.17">6.1.28.17</xref></note>
When I married a malicious husband -- when I bore a malicious son.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.41" type="proverb" n="14.41"><p id="t6114.p22" n="23-25" corresp="c6114.B.14.41.23">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.125">6.1.01.125</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.22">6.1.22: l. 33</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.23" from="t.6.1.23.2">6.1.23.2</xref></note>
My husband heaps up for me, my child measures out for me; my lover picks the bones from the fish for me.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.42" type="proverb" n="14.42"><p id="t6114.p23" n="26" corresp="c6114.B.14.42.26">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.126">6.1.01.126</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.19" from="t.6.1.19.c6">6.1.19.c6</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.22">6.1.22: l. 34</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.3" from="t623.h8">6.2.3: UET 6/2 284</xref></note>
A plant as sweet as a husband does not grow in the desert.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.43" type="proverb" n="14.43"><p id="t6114.p24" n="27" corresp="c6114.B.14.43.27">
My husband needn't bring me grass; it will not make a decoration for my genitals <note lang="eng">idiom: sense unclear</note>.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.44" type="proverb" n="14.44"><p id="t6114.p25" n="28" corresp="c6114.B.14.44.28">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.154">6.1.01.154</xref></note>
A malicious wife living in a house is the worst of all afflictions.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.45" type="proverb" n="14.45"><p id="t6114.p26" n="29-30" corresp="c6114.B.14.45.29">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.22">6.1.22: ll. 35-37</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-15-748 ll. 6-7</xref></note>
A pig was carrying something (?): <q>Where is my sow?</q> it said. As it neared its fate, it said: <q>It is my dung-spattered (?) food!</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.46" type="proverb" n="14.46"><p id="t6114.p27" n="31" corresp="c6114.B.14.46.31">
As for a daughter-in-law -- what about making a reed mat?</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.46a" type="proverb" n="14.46a"><p id="t6114.p28" n="32-33" corresp="c6114.B.14.46a.32">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.169">6.1.01.169</xref></note>
As for the fianc&eacute;, what has he brought? And as for the father-in-law, what has he sorted out?</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.47" type="proverb" n="14.47"><p id="t6114.p29" n="34-35" corresp="c6114.B.14.47.34">
The fianc&eacute; brought &X;&X; did not come out.
<gap extent="approx. 7 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="C">
<lg id="t.6.1.14.55" type="proverb" n="14.55"><p id="t6114.p30" n="1" corresp="c6114.C.14.55.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.15" from="t.6.1.15.c4">6.1.15.c4</xref></note>
A stranger is leader in a foreign city.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.56" type="proverb" n="14.56"><p id="t6114.p31" n="2-4" corresp="c6114.C.14.56.2">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.15" from="t.6.1.15.c5">6.1.15.c5</xref></note>
I am one who does not &X;&X;. I can &X;&X;. I can &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.57" type="proverb" n="14.57"><p id="t6114.p32" n="5-6" corresp="c6114.C.14.57.5">
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.58" type="proverb" n="14.58"><p id="t6114.p33" n="7" corresp="c6114.C.14.58.7">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.59" type="proverb" n="14.59"><p id="t6114.p34" n="8-11" corresp="c6114.C.14.59.8">
<gap extent="4 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.60" type="proverb" n="14.60"><p id="t6114.p35" n="12" corresp="c6114.C.14.60.12">
&X;&X; barley (?) &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.61" type="proverb" n="14.61"><p id="t6114.p36" n="13" corresp="c6114.C.14.61.13">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.62" type="proverb" n="14.62"><p id="t6114.p37" n="14-17" corresp="c6114.C.14.62.14">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.26" from="t.6.1.26.d14">6.1.26.d14</xref></note>
The nights are fifty, the days are fifty; at its &X;&X;, &X;&X; greatly.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.14.63" type="proverb" n="14.63"><p id="t6114.p38" n="18-19" corresp="c6114.C.14.63.18">
